heshire, England"},"en":{"1349–":"1349–Deceased","1349–Male":"1349–Deceased","1355–Female":"1355–Deceased","1387–1437":"1387–1437","1309–Male":"1309–Deceased","1349":"1349","1437":"1437","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1382":"1382","1309":"1309","Horton morris ":"Horton, Manitoba, Canada","Hartford, Cheshire, England":"Hartford, Cheshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Horton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Staffordshire and Warwickshire): habitational name from one or other of the many places so called, such as those in Berkshire, Buckinghamshire, Dorset, Gloucestershire, Herefordshire, Northamptonshire, Shropshire, Somerset, Staffordshire, Wiltshire, and Yorkshire. Most of the placenames derive from Old English <i>horh</i> or <i>horu</i> ‘dirt, filth’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’, though some may have different origins, including Horton in Gloucestershire, which may derive from Old English <i>heorot</i> ‘hart, stag’ + <i>tūn</i>."],"variants":[{"name":"Hortin","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  ."]},{"name":"Horten","meanings":["English: variant of   Horton  .","Norwegian: habitational name from any of several farms named Horten, from an unattested word denoting ‘uneven, hard and lumpy soil’."]}]},{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":33,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705197,"age":106,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"William Horton was born in 1349, in Hartford, Cheshire, England as the son of Philip de Horton. He had at least 1 daughter with Agnes Byrches."},"et":{"1349–":"1349–Surnud","1349–Male":"1349–Surnud","1355–Female":"1355–Surnud","1387–1437":"1387–1437","1309–Male":"1309–Surnud","1349":"1349","1437":"1437","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1382":"1382","1309":"1309","Horton morris ":"Horton, Manitoba, Kanada","Hartford, Cheshire, England":"Hartford, Cheshire, England"},"fi":{"1349–":"1349–Kuollut","1349–Male":"1349–Kuollut","1355–Female":"1355–Kuollut","1387–1437":"1387–1437","1309–Male":"1309–Kuollut","1349":"1349","1437":"1437","1455":"1455","1355":"1355","1387":"1387","1382":"1382","1309":"1309","Horton morris ":"Horton, Manitoba, Kanada","Hartford, Cheshire, England":"Hartford, Cheshire, England"},"fr":{"1349–":"1349–Décédé","1349–Male":"1349–Décédé","1355